          "body": "Verse 8 is the chapter's emotional pivot and its most geographically specific moment. The groom calls the bride from Lebanon — from Amana, Senir, and Hermon, from the dens of lions and the mountains of leopards. These are not vague poetic heights; they are the highest, most dangerous ridgelines of the ancient Levant. The bride is depicted as dwelling somewhere inaccessible — elevated, wild, unreachable. And the groom calls her: 'Come with me.' The summons is not a command but an invitation; it is the call of one who has accepted the distance and is crossing it with words. The danger is not minimized — lions and leopards name the genuine hazards of that terrain. The point is that love is not deterred by danger or distance. Canonically, this verse stands in company with the prophets' image of Israel being called from exile and captivity (Isaiah 35:4; 43:5-6; Jeremiah 31:21), and with the New Testament's understanding of Christ descending from the heights to summon His bride (Philippians 2:6-8). The highest mountain becomes a measure of what love is willing to cross."
