        "excerpt": "You are altogether beautiful, my darling, and there is no blemish in you.",
        "body": "The history of interpretation of Song of Solomon divides into three main positions, all held by orthodox scholars. The **allegorical-only** reading, dominant from Origen through much of the medieval period, treats the book as a pure allegory of God's love for Israel (in Jewish reading) or Christ's love for the church (in Christian reading), with the literal meaning being essentially disposable. The **literal-only** reading treats the book as a celebration of human sexual love with no further canonical freight — a wisdom-book perspective on marriage. The **both/and** reading — preferred by Calvin, Keil, Delitzsch, Glickman, Carr, and most contemporary evangelical scholars — holds that the book is genuinely and primarily about human love between a man and a woman, and that this literal meaning is itself theologically significant because it participates in the canon's larger covenant-love narrative.\n\nThe both/and reading is the exegetically strongest. The New Testament nowhere cites Song of Solomon allegorically, but it does apply its imagery. Ephesians 5:25-32 draws on the husband-wife relationship as an analogy for Christ and the church — and when Paul does so, he is drawing on the same creational theology that grounds Song of Solomon: human marriage was designed from creation to be an image of divine covenant love (Genesis 2:24; Ephesians 5:32 — 'this mystery is great'). Song of Solomon is not allegory; it is **typology** — the real thing that prefigures the greater thing, without the lesser reality being negated.\n\nFor chapter 4 specifically, this means the wasf (vv. 1-7) is genuinely a man praising a real woman's real physical beauty, and it is simultaneously a canonical witness to the posture of Christ toward His church — whose blemish He bore so He could declare her without blemish (2 Corinthians 5:21; Ephesians 5:27). The locked garden (v. 12) is a genuine celebration of a real woman's consecrated chastity, and it simultaneously images the mystery of a people set apart for God. These two registers do not compete; they reinforce each other. The literal is honored; the canonical is not suppressed.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Kullek yaphah* (you are altogether beautiful, v.7) — *kullek* is an emphatic second-person feminine form meaning 'you entirely' or 'every part of you.' *Mum* (blemish, defect) is the Levitical technical term for a disqualifying defect in a sacrificial animal or a priest (Leviticus 21:17-23; Numbers 19:2; Deuteronomy 17:1). The groom uses cultic vocabulary to declare total acceptance."
