        "excerpt": "How beautiful you are, my darling, how beautiful you are!",
        "body": "The wasf genre was well-established in the ancient Near East — comparable poems appear in Egyptian love poetry of the New Kingdom (13th-12th centuries BC) and in Ugaritic literature. What distinguishes the wasf in Song of Solomon is its theological context: this is not secular erotic poetry but Scripture, embedded in the wisdom literature of Israel, whose anthropology insists that human bodies are created good (Genesis 1:31) and that physical beauty is a legitimate object of celebration.\n\nThe groom's praise in verses 1-7 works through seven physical features: eyes (v. 1a), hair (v. 1b), teeth (v. 2), lips and mouth (v. 3a), temples (v. 3b), neck (v. 4), and breasts (v. 5). The number seven in Hebrew literature carries the connotation of completeness — seven features named, one verdict rendered: 'altogether beautiful, no blemish.' The structure of the wasf enacts its conclusion: the parts are enumerated so the whole can be declared.\n\nEach simile is drawn from a different domain — pastoral (doves, goats, ewes, fawns), architectural/military (Tower of David, shields), and botanical (pomegranate, lilies). The mixing of domains is not confusion; it is richness. No single category of comparison can contain the woman's beauty. She simultaneously evokes the gentleness of pastoral life, the dignity of military architecture, and the fertility of the cultivated garden. Howard Hendricks observed that the great sin of Bible study is treating a passage as if it contains less than it does; the wasf's mixed comparisons are a formal rebuke to reductionism.\n\nVerse 6 inserts the groom's anticipatory decision: until the day breaks and shadows flee, he will go to the mountain of myrrh and the hill of frankincense. The aromatic geography recalls the bride herself — myrrh and frankincense have already named her garden's contents (vv. 13-14). He is saying: I am going to her. Then verse 7 delivers the wasf's verdict. The movement from description to declaration is the poem's argument: look carefully enough at the beloved, and a total verdict becomes not only possible but inevitable.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Tsammah* (veil, vv. 1, 3) appears only in Song of Solomon and Isaiah 47:2 in the OT. The repeated 'behind your veil' suggests the wasf is set in the context of the wedding — the bride is veiled, and yet the groom's praise penetrates the veil. What he sees is not diminished by what is concealed; the partial glimpse intensifies rather than reduces his declaration."
