        "excerpt": "Come with me from Lebanon, my bride, may you come with me from Lebanon.",
        "body": "Verse 8 marks a structural shift: the groom has finished describing and now begins inviting. The first use of *kallah* (bride) in the chapter appears here — the shift in address is simultaneous with the shift in mode. He has been cataloging; now he is calling. The escalation of terms — 'my bride' → 'my sister, my bride' — concentrates in verses 8-12, the chapter's covenantal core.\n\nThe geography of verse 8 deserves sustained attention. Lebanon, Amana, Senir, and Hermon are the highest ridgelines of the Levant — and they are inhabited by lions and leopards. The bride is not in a garden; she is in a wilderness of danger and height. The groom's summons is therefore not a call from comfort to comfort but from danger to safety, from inaccessibility to presence. This pattern resonates canonically with the prophetic literature: Isaiah 35:4 ('say to those with anxious heart, take courage, fear not'); Isaiah 43:5-6 ('do not fear, for I am with you; I will bring your offspring from the east and gather you from the west; I will say to the north, give them up; and to the south, do not hold them back'). The beloved summoned from mountain heights is Israel called from exile; and in the New Testament's typological register, it is the church called from the world.\n\nVerses 9-11 record the groom's confession of being undone. The doubled *lavav* — 'you have captured my heart... you have captured my heart' — is the poem's most intense self-disclosure. With a single glance. With a single jewel. The groom is confessing that his beloved's power over him is disproportionate to its instrument: one look, one ornament, and he is undone. Keller's reading of this passage is theologically sharp: the lover who confesses being captivated is not manipulated — he is fully engaged. Perfect love does not remain untouched by the beloved; it becomes vulnerable.\n\nThe comparison of her love to wine (v. 10) echoes the bride's own comparison of the groom's love to wine in 1:2 — the language is mirrored back. In the Song's world, each lover says the other's love is better than wine. This is not flattery; it is the recognition that covenant love exceeds every prior pleasure.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Achot kallah* (sister-bride, vv. 9, 10, 11, 12) — the compound appears four times in this chapter and nowhere else in the OT. In Egyptian love poetry, 'sister' (*senet*) is the standard term for the female beloved, indicating deepest relational solidarity. James understood this as indicating relational co-equality within the covenant bond — the bride is not merely the groom's possession but his closest companion."
