        "excerpt": "A garden locked is my sister, my bride, a rock garden locked, a spring sealed up.",
        "body": "The garden metaphor of verses 12-15 is the chapter's most theologically concentrated unit. Three images, three verbs, one declaration: the bride's exclusivity is total and covenantal. *Naal* (locked/bolted) is used for a door that cannot be opened from without — it requires the keeper to open it from within. *Chatam* (sealed) is the word for a signet-seal, the mark of ownership and authentication. The bride is locked, enclosed, sealed: she belongs to one, is marked for one, is opened only by her own will.\n\nThe evangelical tradition is clear that the locked garden is a celebration, not a complaint. Peter Davids and Douglas Moo both note in their treatments of New Testament sexuality that the Song's garden imagery establishes the theological context for the New Testament's high view of sexual fidelity — the body is not the self's to dispose of without reference to covenant (1 Corinthians 6:19-20; 7:4). The locked garden makes verse 16 possible: what is kept becomes a gift; what is given away before the covenant is neither gift nor garden.\n\nWithin the locked garden grow the finest aromatics of the ancient world. The inventory of verses 13-14 is staggering: pomegranates, henna, nard (×2), saffron, calamus, cinnamon, frankincense trees, myrrh, aloes, 'all the finest spices.' This is not one or two pleasant plants — it is an entire paradise of fragrance. The Hebrew word for the garden's structure in verse 13 is *pardes* — an Old Persian loanword meaning 'paradise' or 'enclosed pleasure garden.' The same word appears in Nehemiah 2:8 (the king's forest) and Ecclesiastes 2:5 (Solomon's parks). The bride's interior is a *pardes* — a paradise garden full of the finest things the ancient world could name.\n\nThe olfactory catalog of verses 13-14 carries priestly weight. Nard was used to anoint Jesus before His burial (John 12:3). Myrrh and frankincense were ingredients of the sacred anointing oil and incense of the tabernacle (Exodus 30:23-35). Cinnamon and calamus also appear in the anointing oil formula (Exodus 30:23-24). The bride's garden contains the ingredients of Israel's holiest worship. She is, within her consecrated space, the substance of priestly fragrance. This is not accidental — it is the Song's most explicit connection of the bride's consecrated body to the sacred space of Israel's worship.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Pardes* (orchard/paradise, v.13) — an Old Persian loanword (*pairidaeza*, enclosed garden). Its three OT occurrences (here, Nehemiah 2:8, Ecclesiastes 2:5) all suggest a walled, cultivated, royal garden. The Septuagint used *paradeisos* to translate *gan* (garden) in Genesis 2-3 — the word that gives us 'paradise.' The bride's garden is Eden-vocabulary applied to a woman."
