        "excerpt": "May my beloved come into his garden and eat its choice fruits.",
        "body": "Verse 16 is the chapter's resolution, its most theologically weighted sentence, and the bride's only speech in the entire chapter. Everything that preceded it — the praise, the summons, the garden metaphor — was preparation for this moment. The bride now speaks, and she says three things: she calls the winds, she opens the garden, and she gives it away.\n\nThe invocation of the north and south winds is not mere atmosphere. In the ancient world, wind was understood as the agent that carries fragrance from a garden outward — it makes what is enclosed available to the one approaching. The bride is not simply unlocking a door; she is releasing the fragrance of everything within. Both winds are summoned because she wants no direction uncovered. This is total self-offering, not partial.\n\nThe phrase 'let my beloved come into his garden' carries its weight in the word 'his.' The bride has kept the garden through the entire chapter — it has been implicitly hers. Now she transfers it: it becomes his garden by her gift. This is the covenant logic of self-donation: I give you what I have kept for you, and in giving it, I name you its rightful owner. The parallel in New Testament theology is Paul's description of the marital body in 1 Corinthians 7:4 — 'the wife does not have authority over her own body, but the husband does; and likewise also the husband does not have authority over his own body, but the wife does.' The mutual donation of Song 4:16 and 1 Corinthians 7:4 occupy the same theological space.\n\nThe canonical echo of verse 16 runs forward to Revelation 22:17: 'the Spirit and the bride say, Come.' The posture is identical — the consecrated bride invites. In Song 4:16 she invites the groom into the garden. In Revelation 22:17 the church invites the Lord to return. The verb is the same; the posture is the same; the love is the same. What the Song seeds in the marital moment, Revelation harvests in the eschatological one. The bride who says 'come into his garden' in Song 4:16 is practicing the posture she will occupy at the end of the age.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Dodi* (my beloved, v.16) — from *dod*, the term for beloved/uncle/love that threads through the Song as the bride's primary address for the groom. Its final appearance in this chapter is in the bride's mouth, after she has called the winds: 'let my *dod* come.' The same word that opened chapter 1 ('let him kiss me... for your love is better than wine') closes chapter 4's speech — the entire book's vocabulary of love concentrated in one jussive."
